lux.title: Adds cookies to dismiss banner + Fix visual regressions from functional component work

comments.body:
@axamei The last two commits fix the visual regressions. 

Explanation:
The `/deep/` selector does not work with "functional" components, which provide much faster rendering. The spacing issues in Approvals are the application css overwriting the non-scoped css, so that should be fixed in the Approvals app. Here is [the line of css](https://github.com/pulibrary/approvals/blob/develop/app/assets/stylesheets/application.scss#L57) that should be removed in Approvals now that the `scoped` has been removed from some functional components. 

Also, to correct for the removal of `/deep/`, I created a `style` attribute for tag-items so we can apply the pill to the Approvals cards in a PR to that repo. To make sure there is no visual regression in Approvals, we will need to simply add a `style: 'pill'` property to the tag-items when building the cards, [like in this line](https://github.com/pulibrary/approvals/blob/develop/app/views/travel_requests/_index_detail.html.erb#L15).

Unless I'm missing something, I don't think we can prevent a breaking change when trying to accommodate the changes required in the functional component work. It's not something we have to do right away, but we can create an issue in the Approvals repo in case we need to update LUX over there. I will update the semver appropriately when releasing. LMK what you think, and merge if you are 👍 .

comments.body:
```python
import json
import os
import pandas as pd

# collect the raw data from the nomisma scrape
dir_path = "nomisma/data/raw/"
all_coins = []
for filename in os.listdir(dir_path):
    if filename.endswith('.json'):
        with open(os.path.join(dir_path, filename)) as f:
            all_coins.append(json.load(f))
            
# Get all unique keys and pair with example
unique_keys = {}
for coin in all_coins:
    for key in j.keys():
        coin_url = f"https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog/{coin['id']}"
        unique_keys[key] = coin_url

# Get a boolean table to consistency of fields
df = pd.DataFrame(index=[coin['id'] for coin in all_coins])
for key in unique_keys:
    df[key] = [key in coin for coin in all_coins]
round(df.sum() / df.count() * 100, 2).sort_values(ascending=False)
```
